# Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture

**Type:** Cultural Institution  
**Date Created:** 2025-01-26  
**Last Updated:** 2025-01-26  

## Overview  

The **Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture** is one of the world’s leading institutions dedicated to the preservation and study of materials related to African, African American, and African diaspora experiences. Located in **Harlem, New York City**, the Schomburg Center serves as a research library, cultural hub, and educational resource committed to documenting Black history and culture.  

---

## Key Details  

- **Founded:** 1925  
- **Location:** 515 Malcolm X Blvd, Harlem, New York City  
- **Affiliation:** Part of the New York Public Library (NYPL) system  
- **Named After:** **[[Arturo Alfonso Schomburg]]**, a Puerto Rican-born scholar and bibliophile who contributed his extensive collection to the NYPL.  
- **Mission:** To preserve and share the rich history and contributions of the African diaspora.  
- **Website:** [Schomburg Center](https://www.nypl.org/locations/schomburg)  

---

## Timeline  

- **1925 (20th Century):** The center was established as the "Division of Negro Literature, History, and Prints" within the NYPL.  
- **1926 (20th Century):** Arturo Schomburg's private collection of over 10,000 items was purchased and incorporated.  
- **1940 (20th Century):** Renamed the Schomburg Collection of Negro Literature, History, and Prints.  
- **1972 (20th Century):** Officially renamed the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture.  
- **1980 (20th Century):** Designated as a National Historic Landmark.  
- **2020 (21st Century):** Celebrated its 95th anniversary with expanded digital collections and online exhibitions.  

